            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Brandon Santos, now 30, arrived in San Francisco just before his 25th birthday, drawn by the promise of a fresh start. He grew up in a working-class household in a small town outside Sacramento. His father worked construction, his mother as a cashier. Life was simple, marked by a strong sense of community but limited opportunity. Brandon wasn't academically inclined, finding school challenging and dropping out at 17 to work odd jobs. This early experience instilled in him a deep appreciation for stability and routine.\n\nHis move to the city was a turning point. Initially adrift, he bounced between temporary jobs before finding work as a school bus monitor. The regular hours and sense of purpose appealed to him. He soon pursued the necessary licensing and became a full-fledged school bus driver. This steady profession at $55,000 a year has provided him with the stability he craved.\n\nBrandon's personal life is centered on a small but close-knit group of friends he\u2019s made through work. He\u2019s never been one for grand romantic gestures, preferring quiet evenings and shared meals. His most significant relationship was a brief but intense one that ended amicably a couple of years ago, leaving him content with his current independent status.\n\nHis daily routine is dictated by the school calendar. Up before dawn, he navigates the city's winding streets, his bus a mobile microcosm of San Francisco's diverse population. He finds unexpected satisfaction in the brief interactions with the children and their parents, a small but meaningful form of connection. His afternoons and evenings are his own, often spent catching up on shows, exercising, or exploring different neighborhoods, trying new, affordable eateries.\n\nBrandon lives in a modest apartment in the Richmond District, appreciating the neighborhood's quiet, residential feel and proximity to Golden Gate Park. San Francisco, with its constant energy and diverse communities, feels a world away from his quiet upbringing, yet he\u2019s found his niche, a comfortable rhythm in the city's busy pulse. His aspirations are simple: continued stability, maybe saving enough for a down payment on a small condo outside the city someday, and the enduring hope for genuine connection, a steady hand to hold as he navigates life's journey."
        },
